Kate Gordon

Bio

Kate Gordon studies the epidemiology and biostatistics of aging. Her research focuses on cognitive aging and the impact of living alone with, or at high risk of, cognitive impairment. She frequently collaborates with researchers who study risk factors for cognitive decline, living well with dementia, and caregiver outcomes.

Education

Johns Hopkins University | Baltimore, MD

Ph.D. in Public Health | Expected Graduation: May 2027 T32

The University of South Carolina | Columbia, SC

M.S.W. in Social Work | 1999 - 2001

Roanoke College | Salem, VA

B.S. in Sociology | 1995 - 1999

Experience

Splaine Consulting | Director | March 2013 - Present

RTI International | Health Policy Analyst | June 2010 - July 2024

Alzheimer’s Disease International | Policy Adviser | April 2013 - December 2018

Alzheimer’s Association | Senior Associate Director, Advocacy | June 2001 - May 2010
